04 - Fluorinated xenobiotics analysis¶

Overview¶

This notebook analyzes the distribution of fluorine-containing compounds (putative xenobiotics) across food categories, with particular focus on animal products and dairy subcategories.

Background¶

Fluorine is rare in natural products but common in synthetic compounds including pharmaceuticals, pesticides, and per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS). The presence of fluorinated compounds in food likely indicates xenobiotic contamination from various sources.

Input data¶

ptfi_data_long.csv - PTFI features in long format

  • sample_id, sample_foodon_leaf_name, metabolite, intensity, element_id

ptfi_non_np_atoms.csv - Non-natural product elemental composition

  • element_id: Metabolite identifier
  • has_F: Boolean flag for fluorine-containing compounds
  • formula: Molecular formula

ptfi_metadata.csv - Sample metadata with FoodOn hierarchy

  • sample_id, foodon_level1_name, foodon_level2_name, foodon_level3_name, foodon_level4_name

Outputs¶

  1. Heatmap: Fluorinated compounds across FoodOn Level 1 categories
  2. Heatmap: Fluorinated compounds in animal product subcategories (Level 4)
  3. Heatmap: Fluorinated compounds in dairy products (sample-level)

    on="sample_id"
)

Helper functions¶

def create_heatmap_df_from_long(
    long_df,
    category_col,
    metabolite_col,
    value_col,
    foodon_filter=None,
    foodon_level_filter=None,
    top_n=10,
    apply_log=False
):
    """
    Create heatmap-ready DataFrame by selecting top N metabolites per category.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    long_df : DataFrame
        Long-format data
    category_col : str
        Column for categories (rows in heatmap)
    metabolite_col : str
        Column for metabolites (columns in heatmap)
    value_col : str
        Column for values to aggregate
    foodon_filter : list or None
        List of FoodOn categories to include
    foodon_level_filter : int or None
        FoodOn level to filter on (1-4)
    top_n : int
        Number of top metabolites to select per category
    apply_log : bool
        Whether to apply log10(x+1) transformation
        
    Returns:
    --------
    DataFrame: Wide-format heatmap data
    """
    # Filter by FoodOn category if specified
    if foodon_filter and foodon_level_filter:
        foodon_level_name = f"foodon_level{foodon_level_filter}_name"
        long_df = long_df[long_df[foodon_level_name].isin(foodon_filter)]
    
    # Find top N metabolites per category
    mean_values = long_df.groupby([category_col, metabolite_col])[value_col].mean()
    top_metabolites_per_category = mean_values.groupby(
        level=0, group_keys=False
    ).nlargest(top_n)
    
    # Get master list of all top metabolites
    master_metabolite_list = top_metabolites_per_category.index.get_level_values(
        metabolite_col
    ).unique()
    
    print(f"Selected {len(master_metabolite_list)} top metabolites across all categories")
    
    # Create wide-format heatmap data
    final_plot_df = long_df[long_df[metabolite_col].isin(master_metabolite_list)]
    heatmap_df = pd.pivot_table(
        final_plot_df,
        values=value_col,
        index=category_col,
        columns=metabolite_col,
        aggfunc='mean',
        fill_value=0
    )
    
    # Remove zero columns
    heatmap_df = heatmap_df.loc[:, (heatmap_df != 0).any(axis=0)]
    
    # Apply log transformation if requested
    if apply_log:
        heatmap_df = np.log10(heatmap_df + 1)
    
    return heatmap_df


def plot_clustered_heatmap(
    heatmap_df, 
    cbar_label='log₁₀(intensity)', 
    width=None,
    height=None,
    cell_size=0.4,
    font_scale=3.5
):
    """
    Create hierarchically clustered heatmap.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    heatmap_df : DataFrame
        Wide-format heatmap data
    cbar_label : str
        Colorbar label
    width : float or None
        Figure width (auto-calculated if None)
    height : float or None
        Figure height (auto-calculated if None)
    cell_size : float
        Size of each cell in inches
    font_scale : float
        Seaborn font scale
        
    Returns:
    --------
    ClusterGrid: Seaborn clustermap object
    """
    if heatmap_df.empty:
        print("Cannot plot heatmap: DataFrame is empty")
        return None
    
    # Calculate figure size
    if width is None and height is None:
        width = heatmap_df.shape[1] * cell_size
        height = heatmap_df.shape[0] * cell_size
    
    # Set maximum size
    max_size = 40
    width = min(width, max_size)
    height = min(height, max_size)
    
    # Set font scale
    sns.set(font_scale=font_scale)
    
    # Create clustermap
    g = sns.clustermap(
        heatmap_df,
        figsize=(width, height),
        cmap='viridis',
        annot=False,
        linewidths=0.5,
        cbar_kws={'label': cbar_label},
        cbar_pos=(0.02, 0.5, 0.05, 0.18),
        square=True
    )
    
    # Formatting
    plt.setp(g.ax_heatmap.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
    g.ax_heatmap.set_xlabel('Molecular formula')
    g.ax_heatmap.set_ylabel('')
    g.ax_cbar.set_ylabel(cbar_label)
    
    return g
